fields: A cervical rib that is an anomaly present in 0.2% of people

•The muscles of the thoracic wall consist of three layers of intercostal muscles:
{{c1::•external intercostals}}
{{c2::•internal intercostals}}
{{c3::•innermost intercostals}}
The {{c1::transversus thoracis muscles}} are also known as {{c2::innermost intercostals}}
The arrows point to {{c1::transversus thoracis muscles (innermost intercostals)}}.
The arrow is pointing to the {{c1::subcostal}} muscle. Which is equivalent to {{c1::innermost intercostals}}.

•pathway of preganglionic and postganglionic sympathetic nerves
•4 possibilities:
•synapse at {{c1::same}} level
•travel {{c1::up}} chain and synapse at higher level
•travel down chain and synapse at {{c1::lower}} level
•pass through chain without synapsing ({{c1::splanchnic nerve::example}}); synapse outside sympathetic chain

The boundaries for the superior thoracic aperture are from:
the {{c1::sternum to the 1st rib to the 1st thoracic vertebra}}.
These arrows show the {{c1::inferior thoracic aperture}}
The boundaries for the {{c2::lower thoracic aperture}} is {{c1::T12 vertebra, 12th ribs, costal cartilages, hiphisternal joint}}.
The {{c1::diaphragm}} covers the opening of the {{c2::lower thoracic apertures}}.
The inferior vena cava passes through at {{c1::T8}} level.
The esophagus passes through at the {{c1::T10}} level of the thoracic aperture.
The aorta passes behind at {{c1::T12}} level of the thoracic aperture.

When {{c1::inspiration}} happens, the {{c1::vertical}} diameter of the diaphragm {{c1::increases}} due to the {{c2::lowering}} of the diaphram. 
The {{c2::transverse}} and {{c2::anteroposterior}} diameters are increased due to the action of {{c1::intercostals}}.
When expiration happens, there is an {{c1::increase::increase/decrease}} in intrathoracic pressure.

The primary brochi
The right bronchus is more {{c1::vertical::horizontal/vertical}}, has a {{c1::larger::smaller/larger}} diameter, and is {{c1::shorter::shorter/longer}}.
The arrows point to the {{c1::bronchial arteries}}
Each box represents the {{c1::bronchopulmonary}} nodes, the {{c1::tracheobronchial}} nodes, and the {{c1::paratrachial}} nodes.
The innervation of the lungs include the pulmonary plexuses. The {{c1::parasympathetics}} come from the {{c2::vagus}} nerve and the {{c1::sympathetics}} come from the {{c2::trunk}}.
